A Search and Rescue team in search of a missing person, found skeletal remains  in a citrus orchard off of Camarillo Springs Road in Camarillo.  The remains were found near a cash register with the faded date (possibly 06 02 13), three pairs of jeans, a blue glass bottle with the engraving "Bromo- Seltzer Emerson Drug Co Baltimore, MD" on it and a partially buried hub cap.

Skeletal remains, designated "John Doe #06-70," found scattered in the desert of Cronise Valley, south of Baker, CA.  Full upper and lower dentures found at scene and mandible (no skull found).  Information developed at scene indicated that decedent may be "J.H. Mollenaar."  Identity can only be established by DNA.  Currently only partial DNA profile can be developed (2 locus STR).  California lab attempting to develop mtDNA).

Body was found in the Detroit River-Possible drowning victim.  It appeared to have been in the water for several weeks to months.  The Anthropologist noted that this person was probably Black, but may have had some white admixture as pertaining to his race.

Partial jaw bone located on Lake Huron beach. The bone was located on the beach approximately 20 feet west of the water's edge approximately 30 feet south of the boardwalk leading to the beach. The bone was in the sand mixed with some dry weeds and small sticks.

Remains were found on George Rd, just north of Noland Rd (KCMO) by a stranger while looking for firewood in a desolate area. The finder removed the remains off the roadway and placed them in a box and took them home. That is when he notified police. He removed the remains because he was afraid dogs would carry them off. No one was seen at or near the recovery site when remains were found.

On 09/17/1983, these skeletal remains were discovered in a desert wash at the west end of Ann Rd. A .22 semi-automatic pistol was recovered from the scene. Based on clothing recovered, it is believed that the decedent's death took place during the winter time. It was suggested that during the decedent's younger years he was probably around 5'10" but due to severe arthritis, his stature at the time of his death was around 5'8". The decedent also had extensive gold bridgework and numerous porcelain facings that would have been very expensive.

On 07/26/1983, these skeletal remains were found scattered in the desert area 1.5 miles southeast of Craig Rd. and 1/4 mile east of Highland Dr. A burned mattress and charred skull were found at the site. Charred bone fragments were found beneath the mattress.

Hunters found the skeletal remains of this decedent and of an older male (UP6507) together in woods in Caroline County off VA I-95. DNA testing indicated a possible parent-child relationship. Both are wearing new clothes. Interval between date of death and date found is approximately 2-10 months.

The remains of an unidentified male, likely white/hispanic, were found off a rural highway . He had multiple distinctive tattoos, all in Spanish. Based off the tattoos it was surmised that he likely came from a Cuban background. The interval between date of death and date found is several days to several weeks.
